      "writtenOn": "2019-08-28T07:17:05Z",
      "side": 1,
      "message": "Removed GetWithDefault().  I don\u0027t find the value of keeping GetWithDefault(), either. As I mentioned in another comment, I\u0027d love to remove SetDefaultTarget() to get rid of the possibility, where the type of the default target can change dynamically.\n\n\n```\n// The default target is a Task\ns.SetDefaultTarget(Task{...})\n\n// Increase the value of the metric from 0 to 1.\n// Is the value for the Task target?\nm.Incr(1)\n\n// The default target is now a Device.\ns.SetDefaultTarget(Device{...})\n\n// Increase the value of the metric again.\n// As a result, the value increases from 1 to 2.\n// Wait, isn\u0027t this the first time of metric.Incr()\n// after a new Target object set via SetDefaultTarget()?\n// Shouldn\u0027t the value from 0 to 1???\nm.Incr(1)\n\n// Set the default Target back to a Task\ns.SetDefaultTarget(Task{...})\n\n// Flush() will report a SINGLE cell, not TWO.\n// Because the cells are given nil for the target,\n// if there is no target in the context, and all the metric data\n// with nil in Tsrget are considered as the same, single cell.\ninterface.state.Flush()\n\n// Of course, target.Set() has a very different semantic.\n```",
